# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: deep-reinforcement-learning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] AlphaGo and its successors use a Monte Carlo tree search algorithm to find its moves based on knowledge previously acquired by machine learning, specifically by an artificial neural network (a deep learning method) by extensive training, both from human and computer play.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] A neural network is trained to identify the best moves and the winning percentages of these moves.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] This neural network improves the strength of the tree search, resulting in stronger move selection in the next iteration.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] In October 2015, in a match against Fan Hui, the original AlphaGo became the first computer Go program to beat a human professional Go player without handicap on a full-sized 19×19 board.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] In March 2016, it beat Lee Sedol in a five-game match, the first time a computer Go program has beaten a 9-dan professional without handicap.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Although it lost to Lee Sedol in the fourth game, Lee resigned in the final game, giving a final score of 4 games to 1 in favour of AlphaGo.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] In recognition of the victory, AlphaGo was awarded an honorary 9-dan by the Korea Baduk Association.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] The lead up and the challenge match with Lee Sedol were documented in a documentary film also titled *AlphaGo*, directed by Greg Kohs.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] The win by AlphaGo was chosen by *Science* as one of the Breakthrough of the Year runners-up on 22 December 2016.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] At the 2017 Future of Go Summit, the Master version of AlphaGo beat Ke Jie, the number one ranked player in the world at the time, in a three-game match, after which AlphaGo was awarded professional 9-dan by the Chinese Weiqi Association.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] After the match between AlphaGo and Ke Jie, DeepMind retired AlphaGo, while continuing AI research in other areas.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] The self-taught AlphaGo Zero achieved a 100–0 victory against the early competitive version of AlphaGo, and its successor AlphaZero was perceived as the world's top player in Go by the end of the 2010s.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Almost two decades after IBM's computer Deep Blue beat world chess champion Garry Kasparov in the 1997 match, the strongest Go programs using artificial intelligence techniques only reached about amateur 5-dan level, and still could not beat a professional Go player without a handicap.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] In 2012, the software program Zen, running on a four PC cluster, beat Masaki Takemiya (9p) twice at five- and four-stone handicaps.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] In 2013, Crazy Stone beat Yoshio Ishida (9p) at a four-stone handicap.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] According to DeepMind's David Silver, the AlphaGo research project was formed around 2014 to test how well a neural network using deep learning can compete at Go.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] AlphaGo represents a significant improvement over previous Go programs.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] In 500 games against other available Go programs, including Crazy Stone and Zen, AlphaGo running on a single computer won all but one.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] In a similar matchup, AlphaGo running on multiple computers won all 500 games played against other Go programs, and 77% of games played against AlphaGo running on a single computer.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] The distributed version in October 2015 was using 1,202 CPUs and 176 GPUs.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] In October 2015, the distributed version of AlphaGo defeated the European Go champion Fan Hui, a 2-dan (out of 9 dan possible) professional, five to zero.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] This was the first time a computer Go program had beaten a professional human player on a full-sized board without handicap.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] The announcement of the news was delayed until 27 January 2016 to coincide with the publication of a paper in the journal *Nature* describing the algorithms used.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] AlphaGo played South Korean professional Go player Lee Sedol, ranked 9-dan, one of the best players at Go, with five games taking place at the Four Seasons Hotel in Seoul, South Korea on 9, 10, 12, 13, and 15 March 2016, which were video-streamed live.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Out of five games, AlphaGo won four games and Lee won the fourth game which made him recorded as the only human player who beat AlphaGo in all of its 74 official games.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] AlphaGo ran on Google's cloud computing with its servers located in the United States.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] The match used Chinese rules with a 7.5-point komi, and each side had two hours of thinking time plus three 60-second byoyomi periods.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] The version of AlphaGo playing against Lee used a similar amount of computing power as was used in the Fan Hui match.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] *The Economist* reported that it used 1,920 CPUs and 280 GPUs.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] At the time of play, Lee Sedol had the second-highest number of Go international championship victories in the world after South Korean player Lee Chang-ho who kept the world championship title for 16 years.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Since there is no single official method of ranking in international Go, the rankings may vary among the sources.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] While he was ranked top sometimes, some sources ranked Lee Sedol as the fourth-best player in the world at the time.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] AlphaGo was not specifically trained to face Lee nor was designed to compete with any specific human players.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] The first three games were won by AlphaGo following resignations by Lee.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] However, Lee beat AlphaGo in the fourth game, winning by resignation at move 180.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] AlphaGo then continued to achieve a fourth win, winning the fifth game by resignation.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Since AlphaGo won four out of five and thus the series, the prize will be donated to charities, including UNICEF.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Lee Sedol received $150,000 for participating in all five games and an additional $20,000 for his win in Game 4.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Before move 78, AlphaGo was leading throughout the game, but Lee's move caused the program's computing powers to be diverted and confused.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] On 29 December 2016, a new account on the Tygem server named "Magister" (shown as 'Magist' at the server's Chinese version) from South Korea began to play games with professional players.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] It changed its account name to "Master" on 30 December, then moved to the FoxGo server on 1 January 2017.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] On 4 January, DeepMind confirmed that the "Magister" and the "Master" were both played by an updated version of AlphaGo, called AlphaGo Master.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] As of 5 January 2017, AlphaGo Master's online record was 60 wins and 0 losses, including three victories over Go's top-ranked player, Ke Jie, who had been quietly briefed in advance that Master was a version of AlphaGo.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] After losing to Master, Gu Li offered a bounty of 100,000 yuan (US$14,400) to the first human player who could defeat Master.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Master played at the pace of 10 games per day.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Many quickly suspected it to be an AI player due to little or no resting between games.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] All 60 games except one were fast-paced games with three 20 or 30 seconds byo-yomi.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Master offered to extend the byo-yomi to one minute when playing with Nie Weiping in consideration of his age.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] After winning its 59th game Master revealed itself in the chatroom to be controlled by Dr.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Aja Huang of the DeepMind team, then changed its nationality to the United Kingdom.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] After these games were completed, the co-founder of DeepMind, Demis Hassabis, said in a tweet, "we're looking forward to playing some official, full-length games later [2017] in collaboration with Go organizations and experts".
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Go experts were impressed by the program's performance and its nonhuman play style; Ke Jie stated that "After humanity spent thousands of years improving our tactics, computers tell us that humans are completely wrong...
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] In the Future of Go Summit held in Wuzhen in May 2017, AlphaGo Master played three games with Ke Jie, the world No.1 ranked player, as well as two games with several top Chinese professionals, one pair Go game and one against a collaborating team of five human players.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Google DeepMind offered 1.5 million dollar winner prizes for the three-game match between Ke Jie and Master while the losing side took 300,000 dollars.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Master won all three games against Ke Jie, after which AlphaGo was awarded professional 9-dan by the Chinese Weiqi Association.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] After winning its three-game match against Ke Jie, the top-rated world Go player, AlphaGo retired.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] DeepMind also disbanded the team that worked on the game to focus on AI research in other areas.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] After the Summit, DeepMind published 50 full length AlphaGo vs AlphaGo matches, as a gift to the Go community.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] AlphaGo's team published an article in the journal *Nature* on 19 October 2017, introducing AlphaGo Zero, a version without human data and stronger than any previous human-champion-defeating version.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] By playing games against itself, AlphaGo Zero surpassed the strength of AlphaGo Lee in three days by winning 100 games to 0, reached the level of AlphaGo Master in 21 days, and exceeded all the old versions in 40 days.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] On 11 December 2017, DeepMind released an AlphaGo teaching tool on its website to analyze winning rates of different Go openings as calculated by AlphaGo Master.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] The teaching tool collects 6,000 Go openings from 230,000 human games each analyzed with 10,000,000 simulations by AlphaGo Master.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Many of the openings include human move suggestions.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] An early version of AlphaGo was tested on hardware with various numbers of CPUs and GPUs, running in asynchronous or distributed mode.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Two seconds of thinking time was given to each move.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] The resulting Elo ratings are listed below.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] In the matches with more time per move higher ratings are achieved.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] In May 2016, Google unveiled its own proprietary hardware "tensor processing units", which it stated had already been deployed in multiple internal projects at Google, including the AlphaGo match against Lee Sedol.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] In the Future of Go Summit in May 2017, DeepMind disclosed that the version of AlphaGo used in this Summit was AlphaGo Master, and revealed that it had measured the strength of different versions of the software.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] AlphaGo Lee, the version used against Lee, could give AlphaGo Fan, the version used in AlphaGo vs.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Fan Hui, three stones, and AlphaGo Master was even three stones stronger.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] As of 2016, AlphaGo's algorithm uses a combination of machine learning and tree search techniques, combined with extensive training, both from human and computer play.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] It uses Monte Carlo tree search, guided by a "value network" and a "policy network", both implemented using deep neural network technology.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] A limited amount of game-specific feature detection pre-processing (for example, to highlight whether a move matches a nakade pattern) is applied to the input before it is sent to the neural networks.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] The networks are convolutional neural networks with 12 layers, trained by reinforcement learning.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] The system's neural networks were initially bootstrapped from human gameplay expertise.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] AlphaGo was initially trained to mimic human play by attempting to match the moves of expert players from recorded historical games, using a database of around 30 million moves.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Once it had reached a certain degree of proficiency, it was trained further by being set to play large numbers of games against other instances of itself, using reinforcement learning to improve its play.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] To avoid "disrespectfully" wasting its opponent's time, the program is specifically programmed to resign if its assessment of win probability falls beneath a certain threshold; for the match against Lee, the resignation threshold was set to 20%.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Toby Manning, the match referee for AlphaGo vs.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Fan Hui, has described the program's style as "conservative".
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] AlphaGo's playing style strongly favours greater probability of winning by fewer points over lesser probability of winning by more points.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Its strategy of maximising its probability of winning is distinct from what human players tend to do which is to maximise territorial gains, and explains some of its odd-looking moves.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] It makes a lot of opening moves that have never or seldom been made by humans.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] It likes to use shoulder hits, especially if the opponent is over concentrated.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] AlphaGo's March 2016 victory was a major milestone in artificial intelligence research.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Go had previously been regarded as a hard problem in machine learning that was expected to be out of reach for the technology of the time.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Most experts thought a Go program as powerful as AlphaGo was at least five years away; some experts thought that it would take at least another decade before computers would beat Go champions.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Most observers at the beginning of the 2016 matches expected Lee to beat AlphaGo.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] With games such as checkers (that has been solved by the Chinook computer engine), chess, and now Go won by computers, victories at popular board games can no longer serve as major milestones for artificial intelligence in the way that they used to.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] When compared with Deep Blue or Watson, AlphaGo's underlying algorithms are potentially more general-purpose and may be evidence that the scientific community is making progress towards artificial general intelligence.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Some commentators believe AlphaGo's victory makes for a good opportunity for society to start preparing for the possible future impact of machines with general purpose intelligence.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] In China, AlphaGo was a "Sputnik moment" which helped convince the Chinese government to prioritize and dramatically increase funding for artificial intelligence.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] In 2017, the DeepMind AlphaGo team received the inaugural IJCAI Marvin Minsky medal for Outstanding Achievements in AI.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] "AlphaGo is a wonderful achievement, and a perfect example of what the Minsky Medal was initiated to recognise", said Professor Michael Wooldridge, Chair of the IJCAI Awards Committee.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] "What particularly impressed IJCAI was that AlphaGo achieves what it does through a brilliant combination of classic AI techniques as well as the state-of-the-art machine learning techniques that DeepMind is so closely associated with.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Go is a popular game in China, Japan and Korea, and the 2016 matches were watched by perhaps a hundred million people worldwide.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Many top Go players characterized AlphaGo's unorthodox plays as seemingly-questionable moves that initially befuddled onlookers, but made sense in hindsight: "All but the very best Go players craft their style by imitating top players.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] AlphaGo seems to have totally original moves it creates itself." AlphaGo appeared to have unexpectedly become much stronger, even when compared with its October 2015 match where a computer had beaten a Go professional for the first time ever without the advantage of a handicap.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] The day after Lee's first defeat, Jeong Ahram, the lead Go correspondent for one of South Korea's biggest daily newspapers, said "Last night was very gloomy...
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Many people drank alcohol." The Korea Baduk Association, the organization that oversees Go professionals in South Korea, awarded AlphaGo an honorary 9-dan title for exhibiting creative skills and pushing forward the game's progress.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] China's Ke Jie, an 18-year-old generally recognized as the world's best Go player at the time, initially claimed that he would be able to beat AlphaGo, but declined to play against it for fear that it would "copy my style".
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] As the matches progressed, Ke Jie went back and forth, stating that "it is highly likely that I (could) lose" after analysing the first three matches, but regaining confidence after AlphaGo displayed flaws in the fourth match.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Toby Manning, the referee of AlphaGo's match against Fan Hui, and Hajin Lee, secretary general of the International Go Federation, both reason that in the future, Go players will get help from computers to learn what they have done wrong in games and improve their skills.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] After game two, Lee said he felt "speechless": "From the very beginning of the match, I could never manage an upper hand for one single move.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] It was AlphaGo's total victory." Lee apologized for his losses, stating after game three that "I misjudged the capabilities of AlphaGo and felt powerless." He emphasized that the defeat was "Lee Se-dol's defeat" and "not a defeat of mankind".
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] On Rotten Tomatoes the documentary has an average rating of 100% from 10 reviews.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] He also mentioned that with the passion of Hauschka's Volker Bertelmann, the film's producer, this documentary shows many unexpected sequences, including strategic and philosophical components.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Greg Kohs, the director of the film, said "The complexity of the game of Go, combined with the technical depth of an emerging technology like artificial intelligence seemed like it might create an insurmountable barrier for a film like this.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] The fact that I was so innocently unaware of Go and AlphaGo actually proved to be beneficial.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] But it can teach us profound things about our humanness – the way we play board games, the way we think and feel and grow.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] It's a deep, vast premise, but my hope is, by sharing it, we can discover something within ourselves we never saw before".
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Hajin Lee, a former professional Go player, described this documentary as being "beautifully filmed".
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] In addition to the story itself, the feelings and atmosphere were also conveyed through different scene arrangements.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] For example, the close-up shots of Lee Sedol when he realizes that the AlphaGo AI is intelligent, the atmospheric scene of the Korean commentator's distress and affliction following the first defeat, and the tension being held inside the room.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] The documentary also tells a story by describing the background of AlphaGo technology and the customs of the Korean Go community.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] She suggests some areas to be covered additionally.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] History had been made, and centuries of received learning overturned in the process.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] The program was free to learn the game for itself.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] James Vincent, a reporter from The Verge, comments that "It prods and pokes viewers with unsubtle emotional cues, like a reality TV show would.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] "Now, you should be nervous; now you should feel relieved".
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] The AlphaGo footage slowly captures the moment when Lee Sedol acknowledges the true power of AlphaGo AI.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] In the first game, he had more experience than his human-programmed AI, so he thought it would be easy to beat the AI.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] However, the early game dynamics were not what he expected.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] After losing the first match, he became more nervous and lost confidence.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Afterward, he reacted to attacks by saying that he just wanted to win the match, unintentionally displaying his anger, and acting in an unusual way.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Also, he spends 12 minutes on one move, while AlphaGo only takes a minute and a half to respond.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] AlphaGo weighs each alternative equally and consistently.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Instead, the game continues as if he was not there.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] James also said that "suffice to say that humanity does land at least one blow on the machines, through Lee's so-called "divine move".
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] "More likely, the forces of automation we'll face will be impersonal and incomprehensible.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] They'll come in the form of star ratings we can't object to, and algorithms we can't fully understand.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Dealing with the problems of AI will take a perspective that looks beyond individual battles.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Facebook has also been working on its own Go-playing system *darkforest*, also based on combining machine learning and Monte Carlo tree search.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Although a strong player against other computer Go programs, as of early 2016, it had not yet defeated a professional human player.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Darkforest has lost to CrazyStone and Zen and is estimated to be of similar strength to them.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] DeepZenGo, a system developed with support from video-sharing website Dwango and the University of Tokyo, lost 2–1 in November 2016 to Go master Cho Chikun, who holds the record for the largest number of Go title wins in Japan.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] A 2018 paper in *Nature* cited AlphaGo's approach as the basis for a new means of computing potential pharmaceutical drug molecules.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Systems consisting of Monte Carlo tree search guided by neural networks have since been explored for a wide array of applications.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Tang Weixing (31 December 2016), AlphaGo won by resignation.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] The documentary film *AlphaGo* raised hopes that Lee Sedol and Fan Hui would have benefitted from their experience of playing AlphaGo, but as of May 2018, their ratings were little changed; Lee Sedol was ranked 11th in the world, and Fan Hui 545th.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] On 19 November 2019, Lee announced his retirement from professional play, arguing that he could never be the top overall player of Go due to the increasing dominance of AI.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/alphago] Lee referred to them as being "an entity that cannot be defeated".
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] A **Bellman equation**, named after Richard E.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Bellman, is a technique in dynamic programming which breaks an optimization problem into a sequence of simpler subproblems, as Bellman's "principle of optimality" prescribes.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] It is a necessary condition for optimality.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] The "value" of a decision problem at a certain point in time is written in terms of the payoff from some initial choices and the "value" of the remaining decision problem that results from those initial choices.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] The equation applies to algebraic structures with a total ordering; for algebraic structures with a partial ordering, the generic Bellman's equation can be used.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] The term "Bellman equation" usually refers to the dynamic programming equation (DPE) associated with discrete-time optimization problems.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] In continuous-time optimization problems, the analogous equation is a partial differential equation called the Hamilton–Jacobi–Bellman equation.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] In discrete time any multi-stage optimization problem can be solved by analyzing the appropriate Bellman equation.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] The appropriate Bellman equation can be found by introducing new state variables (state augmentation).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] However, the resulting augmented-state multi-stage optimization problem has a higher dimensional state space than the original multi-stage optimization problem - an issue that can potentially render the augmented problem intractable due to the "curse of dimensionality".
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Alternatively, it has been shown that if the cost function of the multi-stage optimization problem satisfies a "backward separable" structure, then the appropriate Bellman equation can be found without state augmentation.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] To understand the Bellman equation, several underlying concepts must be introduced.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] First, any optimization problem has some objective: minimizing travel time, minimizing cost, maximizing profits, maximizing utility, etc.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] The mathematical function that describes this objective is called the *objective function*.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Dynamic programming breaks a multi-period planning problem into simpler steps at different points in time.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Therefore, it requires keeping track of how the decision situation is evolving over time.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] The information about the current situation that is needed to make a correct decision is called the "state".
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] For example, to decide how much to consume and spend at each point in time, people would need to know (among other things) their initial wealth.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Therefore, wealth $(W)$ would be one of their *state variables*, but there would probably be others.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] The variables chosen at any given point in time are often called the *control variables*.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] For instance, given their current wealth, people might decide how much to consume now.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Choosing the control variables now may be equivalent to choosing the next state; more generally, the next state is affected by other factors in addition to the current control.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] For example, in the simplest case, today's wealth (the state) and consumption (the control) might exactly determine tomorrow's wealth (the new state), though typically other factors will affect tomorrow's wealth too.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] The dynamic programming approach describes the optimal plan by finding a rule that tells what the controls should be, given any possible value of the state.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] For example, if consumption (*c*) depends *only* on wealth (*W*), we would seek a rule $c(W)$ that gives consumption as a function of wealth.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Such a rule, determining the controls as a function of the states, is called a *policy function*.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Finally, by definition, the optimal decision rule is the one that achieves the best possible value of the objective.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] The best possible value of the objective, written as a function of the state, is called the *value function*.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Bellman showed that a dynamic optimization problem in discrete time can be stated in a recursive, step-by-step form known as backward induction by writing down the relationship between the value function in one period and the value function in the next period.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] The relationship between these two value functions is called the "Bellman equation".
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] In this approach, the optimal policy in the last time period is specified in advance as a function of the state variable's value at that time, and the resulting optimal value of the objective function is thus expressed in terms of that value of the state variable.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Thus, each period's decision is made by explicitly acknowledging that all future decisions will be optimally made.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] For a decision that begins at time 0, we take as given the initial state $x_{0}$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] At any time, the set of possible actions depends on the current state; we express this as $a_{t}\in \Gamma (x_{t})$ , where a particular action $a_{t}$ represents particular values for one or more control variables, and $\Gamma (x_{t})$ is the set of actions available to be taken at state $x_{t}$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] It is also assumed that the state changes from x to a new state $T(x,a)$ when action a is taken, and that the current payoff from taking action a in state x is $F(x,a)$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Finally, we assume impatience, represented by a discount factor $0<\beta <1$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Notice that we have defined notation $V(x_{0})$ to denote the optimal value that can be obtained by maximizing this objective function subject to the assumed constraints.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] It is a function of the initial state variable $x_{0}$ , since the best value obtainable depends on the initial situation.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] The dynamic programming method breaks this decision problem into smaller subproblems.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] In computer science, a problem that can be broken apart like this is said to have optimal substructure.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] In the context of dynamic game theory, this principle is analogous to the concept of subgame perfect equilibrium, although what constitutes an optimal policy in this case is conditioned on the decision-maker's opponents choosing similarly optimal policies from their points of view.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] As suggested by the *principle of optimality*, we will consider the first decision separately, setting aside all future decisions (we will start afresh from time 1 with the new state $x_{1}$ ).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Here we are choosing $a_{0}$ , knowing that our choice will cause the time 1 state to be $x_{1}=T(x_{0},a_{0})$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] That new state will then affect the decision problem from time 1 on.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] The whole future decision problem appears inside the square brackets on the right.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] So far it seems we have only made the problem uglier by separating today's decision from future decisions.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] But we can simplify by noticing that what is inside the square brackets on the right is *the value* of the time 1 decision problem, starting from state $x_{1}=T(x_{0},a_{0})$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] The Bellman equation is classified as a functional equation, because solving it means finding the unknown function V , which is the *value function*.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Recall that the value function describes the best possible value of the objective, as a function of the state x .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] By calculating the value function, we will also find the function $a(x)$ that describes the optimal action as a function of the state; this is called the *policy function*.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] In the deterministic setting, other techniques besides dynamic programming can be used to tackle the above optimal control problem.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] However, the Bellman Equation is often the most convenient method of solving *stochastic* optimal control problems.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] For a specific example from economics, consider an infinitely-lived consumer with initial wealth endowment ${\color {Red}a_{0}}$ at period 0 .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] They have an instantaneous utility function $u(c)$ where c denotes consumption and discounts the next period utility at a rate of $0<\beta <1$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Assume that what is not consumed in period t carries over to the next period with interest rate r .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] The first constraint is the capital accumulation/law of motion specified by the problem, while the second constraint is a transversality condition that the consumer does not carry debt at the end of their life.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Alternatively, one can treat the sequence problem directly using, for example, the Hamiltonian equations.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Now, if the interest rate varies from period to period, the consumer is faced with a stochastic optimization problem.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Let the interest *r* follow a Markov process with probability transition function $Q(r,d\mu _{r})$ where $d\mu _{r}$ denotes the probability measure governing the distribution of interest rate next period if current interest rate is r .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] In this model the consumer decides their current period consumption after the current period interest rate is announced.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] The expectation $\mathbb {E}$ is taken with respect to the appropriate probability measure given by *Q* on the sequences of *r*'s.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Because *r* is governed by a Markov process, dynamic programming simplifies the problem significantly.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Under some reasonable assumption, the resulting optimal policy function *g*(*a*,*r*) is measurable.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] The first known application of a Bellman equation in economics is due to Martin Beckmann and Richard Muth.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Martin Beckmann also wrote extensively on consumption theory using the Bellman equation in 1959.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] A celebrated economic application of a Bellman equation is Robert C.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Merton's seminal 1973 article on the intertemporal capital asset pricing model.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] The solution to Merton's theoretical model, one in which investors chose between income today and future income or capital gains, is a form of Bellman's equation.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Because economic applications of dynamic programming usually result in a Bellman equation that is a difference equation, economists refer to dynamic programming as a "recursive method" and a subfield of recursive economics is now recognized within economics.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Lucas, and Edward Prescott describe stochastic and nonstochastic dynamic programming in considerable detail, and develop theorems for the existence of solutions to problems meeting certain conditions.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] They also describe many examples of modeling theoretical problems in economics using recursive methods.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] This book led to dynamic programming being employed to solve a wide range of theoretical problems in economics, including optimal economic growth, resource extraction, principal–agent problems, public finance, business investment, asset pricing, factor supply, and industrial organization.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Lars Ljungqvist and Thomas Sargent apply dynamic programming to study a variety of theoretical questions in monetary policy, fiscal policy, taxation, economic growth, search theory, and labor economics.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Avinash Dixit and Robert Pindyck showed the value of the method for thinking about capital budgeting.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Anderson adapted the technique to business valuation, including privately held businesses.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] Using dynamic programming to solve concrete problems is complicated by informational difficulties, such as choosing the unobservable discount rate.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] There are also computational issues, the main one being the curse of dimensionality arising from the vast number of possible actions and potential state variables that must be considered before an optimal strategy can be selected.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] For an extensive discussion of computational issues, see Miranda and Fackler, and Meyn 2007.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] In Markov decision processes, a Bellman equation is a recursion for expected rewards.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] This equation describes the expected reward for taking the action prescribed by some policy $\pi$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] where ${\pi *}$ is the optimal policy and $V^{\pi *}$ refers to the value function of the optimal policy.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/bellman-equation] The equation above describes the reward for taking the action giving the highest expected return.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Deep learning is a form of machine learning that transforms a set of inputs into a set of outputs via an artificial neural network.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] In the past decade, deep RL has achieved remarkable results on a range of problems, from single and multiplayer games such as Go, Atari Games, and *Dota 2* to robotics.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Reinforcement learning is a process in which an agent learns to make decisions through trial and error.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] This problem is often modeled mathematically as a Markov decision process (MDP), where an agent at every timestep is in a state s , takes action a , receives a scalar reward and transitions to the next state $s'$ according to environment dynamics $p(s'|s,a)$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] The agent attempts to learn a policy $\pi (a|s)$ , or map from observations to actions, in order to maximize its returns (expected sum of rewards).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] In reinforcement learning (as opposed to optimal control) the algorithm only has access to the dynamics $p(s'|s,a)$ through sampling.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] In many practical decision-making problems, the states s of the MDP are high-dimensional (e.g., images from a camera or the raw sensor stream from a robot) and cannot be solved by traditional RL algorithms.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Deep reinforcement learning algorithms incorporate deep learning to solve such MDPs, often representing the policy $\pi (a|s)$ or other learned functions as a neural network and developing specialized algorithms that perform well in this setting.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Along with rising interest in neural networks beginning in the mid 1980s, interest grew in deep reinforcement learning, where a neural network is used in reinforcement learning to represent policies or value functions.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Because in such a system, the entire decision making process from sensors to motors in a robot or agent involves a single neural network, it is also sometimes called end-to-end reinforcement learning.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] One of the first successful applications of reinforcement learning with neural networks was TD-Gammon, a computer program developed in 1992 for playing backgammon.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Four inputs were used for the number of pieces of a given color at a given location on the board, totaling 198 input signals.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] With zero knowledge built in, the network learned to play the game at an intermediate level by self-play and TD( $\lambda$ ).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Seminal textbooks by Sutton and Barto on reinforcement learning, Bertsekas and Tsitiklis on neuro-dynamic programming, and others advanced knowledge and interest in the field.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Starting around 2012, the so-called deep learning revolution led to an increased interest in using deep neural networks as function approximators across a variety of domains.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] This led to a renewed interest in researchers using deep neural networks to learn the policy, value, and/or Q functions present in existing reinforcement learning algorithms.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Beginning around 2013, DeepMind showed impressive learning results using deep RL to play Atari video games.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] The computer player a neural network trained using a deep RL algorithm, a deep version of Q-learning they termed deep Q-networks (DQN), with the game score as the reward.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] They used a deep convolutional neural network to process 4 frames RGB pixels (84x84) as inputs.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] All 49 games were learned using the same network architecture and with minimal prior knowledge, outperforming competing methods on almost all the games and performing at a level comparable or superior to a professional human game tester.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Deep reinforcement learning reached another milestone in 2015 when AlphaGo, a computer program trained with deep RL to play Go, became the first computer Go program to beat a human professional Go player without handicap on a full-sized 19×19 board.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] In a subsequent project in 2017, AlphaZero improved performance on Go while also demonstrating they could use the same algorithm to learn to play chess and shogi at a level competitive or superior to existing computer programs for those games, and again improved in 2019 with MuZero.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Separately, another milestone was achieved by researchers from Carnegie Mellon University in 2019 developing Pluribus, a computer program to play poker that was the first to beat professionals at multiplayer games of no-limit Texas hold 'em.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] OpenAI Five, a program for playing five-on-five *Dota 2* beat the previous world champions in a demonstration match in 2019.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Deep reinforcement learning has also been applied to many domains beyond games.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] In robotics, it has been used to let robots perform simple household tasks and solve a Rubik's cube with a robot hand.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Deep RL has also found sustainability applications, used to reduce energy consumption at data centers.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Deep RL for autonomous driving is an active area of research in academia and industry.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Loon explored deep RL for autonomously navigating their high-altitude balloons.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Various techniques exist to train policies to solve tasks with deep reinforcement learning algorithms, each having their own benefits.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] At the highest level, there is a distinction between model-based and model-free reinforcement learning, which refers to whether the algorithm attempts to learn a forward model of the environment dynamics.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] In **model-based** deep reinforcement learning algorithms, a forward model of the environment dynamics is estimated, usually by supervised learning using a neural network.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Then, actions are obtained by using model predictive control using the learned model.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Since the true environment dynamics will usually diverge from the learned dynamics, the agent re-plans often when carrying out actions in the environment.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] The actions selected may be optimized using Monte Carlo methods such as the cross-entropy method, or a combination of model-learning with model-free methods.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] In **model-free** deep reinforcement learning algorithms, a policy $\pi (a|s)$ is learned without explicitly modeling the forward dynamics.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] A policy can be optimized to maximize returns by directly estimating the policy gradient but suffers from high variance, making it impractical for use with function approximation in deep RL.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Subsequent algorithms have been developed for more stable learning and widely applied.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Another class of model-free deep reinforcement learning algorithms rely on dynamic programming, inspired by temporal difference learning and Q-learning.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] In discrete action spaces, these algorithms usually learn a neural network Q-function $Q(s,a)$ that estimates the future returns taking action a from state s .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] In continuous spaces, these algorithms often learn both a value estimate and a policy.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Deep reinforcement learning is an active area of research, with several lines of inquiry.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] An RL agent must balance the exploration/exploitation tradeoff: the problem of deciding whether to pursue actions that are already known to yield high rewards or explore other actions in order to discover higher rewards.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] RL agents usually collect data with some type of stochastic policy, such as a Boltzmann distribution in discrete action spaces or a Gaussian distribution in continuous action spaces, inducing basic exploration behavior.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] The idea behind novelty-based, or curiosity-driven, exploration is giving the agent a motive to explore unknown outcomes in order to find the best solutions.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] This is done by "modify[ing] the loss function (or even the network architecture) by adding terms to incentivize exploration".
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] An agent may also be aided in exploration by utilizing demonstrations of successful trajectories, or reward-shaping, giving an agent intermediate rewards that are customized to fit the task it is attempting to complete.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] An important distinction in RL is the difference between on-policy algorithms that require evaluating or improving the policy that collects data, and off-policy algorithms that can learn a policy from data generated by an arbitrary policy.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Generally, value-function based methods such as Q-learning are better suited for off-policy learning and have better sample-efficiency - the amount of data required to learn a task is reduced because data is re-used for learning.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] At the extreme, offline (or "batch") RL considers learning a policy from a fixed dataset without additional interaction with the environment.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Inverse RL refers to inferring the reward function of an agent given the agent's behavior.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Inverse reinforcement learning can be used for learning from demonstrations (or apprenticeship learning) by inferring the demonstrator's reward and then optimizing a policy to maximize returns with RL.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Deep learning approaches have been used for various forms of imitation learning and inverse RL.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Another active area of research is in learning goal-conditioned policies, also called contextual or universal policies $\pi (a|s,g)$ that take in an additional goal g as input to communicate a desired aim to the agent.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Hindsight experience replay is a method for goal-conditioned RL that involves storing and learning from previous failed attempts to complete a task.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] While a failed attempt may not have reached the intended goal, it can serve as a lesson for how achieve the unintended result through hindsight relabeling.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Many applications of reinforcement learning do not involve just a single agent, but rather a collection of agents that learn together and co-adapt.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] These agents may be competitive, as in many games, or cooperative as in many real-world multi-agent systems.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Multi-agent reinforcement learning studies the problems introduced in this setting.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] The promise of using deep learning tools in reinforcement learning is generalization: the ability to operate correctly on previously unseen inputs.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] For instance, neural networks trained for image recognition can recognize that a picture contains a bird even it has never seen that particular image or even that particular bird.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Since deep RL allows raw data (e.g. pixels) as input, there is a reduced need to predefine the environment, allowing the model to be generalized to multiple applications.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] With this layer of abstraction, deep reinforcement learning algorithms can be designed in a way that allows them to be general and the same model can be used for different tasks.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] One method of increasing the ability of policies trained with deep RL policies to generalize is to incorporate representation learning.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] There has been a growing body of research on using deep RL for financial problems, particularly portfolio optimization.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Traditional approaches like modern portfolio theory (MPT) rely on mean-variance optimization to balance risk and return.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] However, they often lack the adaptability required in volatile markets.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Deep RL, on the other hand, reframes the problem as a dynamic decision-making process using frameworks like Markov decision processes (MDPs) or partially observed Markov decision processes (POMDPs).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] This approach allows a deep RL agent to continuously interact with the market, making decisions to maximize long-term returns based on evolving data.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Essential components of deep RL models, such as state and action spaces, reward functions, and policy optimization techniques, play a crucial role in this adaptability.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Models like deep deterministic policy gradient (DDPG), and proximal policy optimization (PPO) stand out for their application in continuous action spaces and their potential in handling the complexity of financial markets.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/deep-reinforcement-learning] Implementation of deep RL in the domain of financial problems remains an evolving area of research.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] A **Markov decision process** (**MDP**) is a mathematical model for sequential decision making when outcomes are uncertain.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] It is a type of stochastic decision process, and is often solved using the methods of stochastic dynamic programming.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Originating from operations research in the 1950s, MDPs have since gained recognition in a variety of fields, including ecology, economics, healthcare, telecommunications and reinforcement learning.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Reinforcement learning utilizes the MDP framework to model the interaction between a learning agent and its environment.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] In this framework, the interaction is characterized by states, actions, and rewards.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] The MDP framework is designed to provide a simplified representation of key elements of artificial intelligence challenges.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] This modeling framework incorporates the understanding of cause and effect, the management of uncertainty and nondeterminism, and the pursuit of explicit goals.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] The name comes from its connection to Markov chains, a concept developed by the Russian mathematician Andrey Markov.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] The "Markov" in "Markov decision process" refers to the underlying structure of state transitions that still follow the Markov property.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] The process is called a "decision process" because it involves making decisions that influence these state transitions, extending the concept of a Markov chain into the realm of decision-making under uncertainty.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] A policy function $\pi$ is a (potentially probabilistic) mapping from state space ( S ) to action space ( A ).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] The goal in a Markov decision process is to find a good "policy" for the decision maker: a function $\pi$ that specifies the action $\pi (s)$ that the decision maker will choose when in state s .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Once a Markov decision process is combined with a policy in this way, this fixes the action for each state and the resulting combination behaves like a Markov chain (since the action chosen in state s is completely determined by $\pi (s)$ ).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] where $\ \gamma \$ is the discount factor satisfying $0\leq \ \gamma \ \leq \ 1$ , which is usually close to 1 (for example, $\gamma =1/(1+r)$ for some discount rate r ).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] A lower discount factor makes the decision maker more short-sighted, in that it comparatively disregards the effect that following its current policy has at times lying further in the future.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Another possible, but strictly related, objective that is commonly used is the $H-$ step return.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] This time, instead of using a discount factor $\ \gamma \$ , the agent is interested only in the first H steps of the process, with each reward having the same weight.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Compared to the previous objective, the latter one is more used in Learning Theory.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] A policy that maximizes the function above is called an **optimal policy** and is usually denoted $\pi ^{*}$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] A particular MDP may have multiple distinct optimal policies.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Because of the Markov property, it can be shown that the optimal policy is a function of the current state, as assumed above.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] When $R_{a}(s,s')$ is deterministic, there will always exist an optimal policy $\pi ^{*}$ which is deterministic as well.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Assume that R is deterministic, meaning for constants $a,s,s'$ the value $R_{a}(s,s')$ is also constant.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] From inspection, notice that this fixed point is the value function associated to the following policy.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] By unrolling the Bellman recursion, one can show that $V^{*}$ is indeed optimal (simultaneously for all states) over the set of deterministic policies.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Consider the case where $\pi$ is probabilistic, meaning the action taken $a:=\pi (s)$ is a random variable.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] One can show any such non-deterministic policy is dominated by deterministic $\pi ^{*}$ as follows.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] In many cases, it is difficult to represent the transition probability distributions, $P_{a}(s,s')$ , explicitly.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] In such cases, a simulator can be used to model the MDP implicitly by providing samples from the transition distributions.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] One common form of implicit MDP model is an episodic environment simulator that can be started from an initial state and yields a subsequent state and reward every time it receives an action input.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] In this manner, trajectories of states, actions, and rewards, often called **episodes** may be produced.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Another form of simulator is a **generative model**, a single step simulator that can generate samples of the next state and reward given any state and action.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] (Note that this is a different meaning from the term generative model in the context of statistical classification.) In algorithms that are expressed using pseudocode, G is often used to represent a generative model.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] For example, the expression $s',r\gets G(s,a)$ might denote the action of sampling from the generative model where s and a are the current state and action, and $s'$ and r are the new state and reward.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Compared to an episodic simulator, a generative model has the advantage that it can yield data from any state, not only those encountered in a trajectory.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] These model classes form a hierarchy of information content: an explicit model trivially yields a generative model through sampling from the distributions, and repeated application of a generative model yields an episodic simulator.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] In the opposite direction, it is only possible to learn approximate models through regression.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] The type of model available for a particular MDP plays a significant role in determining which solution algorithms are appropriate.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] An example of MDP is the Pole-Balancing model, which comes from classic control theory.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Solutions for MDPs with finite state and action spaces may be found through a variety of methods such as dynamic programming.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] The algorithms in this section apply to MDPs with finite state and action spaces and explicitly given transition probabilities and reward functions, but the basic concepts may be extended to handle other problem classes, for example using function approximation.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Also, some processes with countably infinite state and action spaces can be *exactly* reduced to ones with finite state and action spaces.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] The standard family of algorithms to calculate optimal policies for finite state and action MDPs requires storage for two arrays indexed by state: *value* V , which contains real values, and *policy* $\pi$ , which contains actions.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] At the end of the algorithm, $\pi$ will contain the solution and $V(s)$ will contain the discounted sum of the rewards to be earned (on average) by following that solution from state s .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] The algorithm has two steps, (1) a value update and (2) a policy update, which are repeated in some order for all the states until no further changes take place.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Both recursively update a new estimation of the optimal policy and state value using an older estimation of those values.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Their order depends on the variant of the algorithm; one can also do them for all states at once or state by state, and more often to some states than others.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] As long as no state is permanently excluded from either of the steps, the algorithm will eventually arrive at the correct solution.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] In value iteration (Bellman 1957), which is also called backward induction, the $\pi$ function is not used; instead, the value of $\pi (s)$ is calculated within $V(s)$ whenever it is needed.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Value iteration starts at $i=0$ and $V_{0}$ as a guess of the value function.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] It then iterates, repeatedly computing $V_{i+1}$ for all states s , until V converges with the left-hand side equal to the right-hand side (which is the "Bellman equation" for this problem).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Lloyd Shapley's 1953 paper on stochastic games included as a special case the value iteration method for MDPs, but this was recognized only later on.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Value iteration is guaranteed to converge for $\gamma <1$ by the Banach fixed-point theorem.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] The Banach fixed-point theorem states that a given contraction mapping has a unique fixed point; further, one can asymptotically approach this fixed points by iterated application of the contraction mapping.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] It then suffices to show that value iteration is a contraction mapping, which is shown below for $\gamma <1$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] In policy iteration, one first performs *Value Determination* by solving for V from the linear system described in step one, then performs *Policy Improvement* by computing $\pi$ as in step two, then repeats both steps until the policy converges.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Since policy iteration effectively interleaves a linear inverse problem with a nonlinear operation, it may interpreted as a type of relaxation method.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] This variant has the advantage that there is a definite stopping condition.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Since there is a unique solution V for each policy $\pi$ , the algorithm is completed once the *Policy Improvement* produces the same policy twice consecutively.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] While there are situations where policy iteration may be faster than value iteration (e.g. when the action space is significantly larger than the state space), policy iteration is usually slower than value iteration for a large number of possible states.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] In modified policy iteration (van Nunen 1976; Puterman & Shin 1978), step one is repeated several times, and then step two is performed once.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Then step one is again repeated several times and so on.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Algorithms for finding optimal policies with time complexity polynomial in the size of the problem representation exist for finite MDPs.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Thus, decision problems based on MDPs are in computational complexity class P.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] However, due to the curse of dimensionality, the size of the problem representation is often exponential in the number of state and action variables, limiting exact solution techniques to problems that have a compact representation.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] A Markov decision process is a stochastic game with only one player.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] The solution above assumes that the state s is known when action is to be taken; otherwise $\pi (s)$ cannot be calculated.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] When this assumption is not true, the problem is called a partially observable Markov decision process or POMDP.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Constrained Markov decision processes (CMDPS) are extensions to Markov decision process (MDPs).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] There are three fundamental differences between MDPs and CMDPs.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] The method of Lagrange multipliers applies to CMDPs.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Many Lagrangian-based algorithms have been developed.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] There are a number of applications for CMDPs.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] It has recently been used in motion planning scenarios in robotics.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] In discrete-time Markov Decision Processes, decisions are made at discrete time intervals.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] However, for **continuous-time Markov decision processes**, decisions can be made at any time the decision maker chooses.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] In comparison to discrete-time Markov decision processes, continuous-time Markov decision processes can better model the decision-making process for a system that has continuous dynamics, i.e., the system dynamics are defined by ordinary differential equations (ODEs).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] This modelling framework can be applied to areas such as queueing systems, epidemic processes, and population processes.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Like the discrete-time Markov decision processes, in continuous-time Markov decision processes the agent aims to find the optimal *policy* that would maximize the expected cumulative reward.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] If the state space and action space are finite, we could use linear programming to find the optimal policy, which was one of the earliest approaches applied.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Here we only consider the ergodic model, which means our continuous-time MDP becomes an ergodic continuous-time Markov chain under a stationary policy.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Under this assumption, although the decision maker can make a decision at any time in the current state, there is no benefit in taking multiple actions.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] It is better to take an action only at the time when system is transitioning from the current state to another state.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] If there exists a function h , then ${\bar {V}}^{*}$ will be the smallest g satisfying the above equation.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] $y(i,a)$ is a feasible solution to the D-LP if $y(i,a)$ is nonnative and satisfied the constraints in the D-LP problem.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] for all feasible solution $y(i,a)$ to the D-LP.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Once we have found the optimal solution $y^{*}(i,a)$ , we can use it to establish the optimal policies.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] In continuous-time MDP, if the state space and action space are continuous, the optimal criterion could be found by solving the Hamilton–Jacobi–Bellman (HJB) partial differential equation.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] $D(\cdot )$ is the terminal reward function, $s(t)$ is the system state vector, $a(t)$ is the system control vector we try to find. $f(\cdot )$ shows how the state vector changes over time.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Reinforcement learning is an interdisciplinary area of machine learning and optimal control that has, as main objective, finding an approximately optimal policy for MDPs where transition probabilities and rewards are unknown.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Reinforcement learning can solve Markov-Decision processes without explicit specification of the transition probabilities which are instead needed to perform policy iteration.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] In this setting, transition probabilities and rewards must be learned from experience, i.e. by letting an agent interact with the MDP for a given number of steps.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] While this function is also unknown, experience during learning is based on $(s,a)$ pairs (together with the outcome $s'$ ; that is, "I was in state s and I tried doing a and $s'$ happened").
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Thus, one has an array Q and uses experience to update it directly.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Another application of MDP process in machine learning theory is called learning automata.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] This is also one type of reinforcement learning if the environment is stochastic.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] The first detail **learning automata** paper is surveyed by Narendra and Thathachar (1974), which were originally described explicitly as finite-state automata.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Similar to reinforcement learning, a learning automata algorithm also has the advantage of solving the problem when probability or rewards are unknown.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] The difference between learning automata and Q-learning is that the former technique omits the memory of Q-values, but updates the action probability directly to find the learning result.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Learning automata is a learning scheme with a rigorous proof of convergence.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] The states of such an automaton correspond to the states of a "discrete-state discrete-parameter Markov process".
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] At each time step *t* = 0,1,2,3,..., the automaton reads an input from its environment, updates P(*t*) to P(*t* + 1) by *A*, randomly chooses a successor state according to the probabilities P(*t* + 1) and outputs the corresponding action.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] The automaton's environment, in turn, reads the action and sends the next input to the automaton.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Other than the rewards, a Markov decision process $(S,A,P)$ can be understood in terms of Category theory.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Namely, let ${\mathcal {A}}$ denote the free monoid with generating set *A*.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Let **Dist** denote the Kleisli category of the Giry monad.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] Then a functor ${\mathcal {A}}\to \mathbf {Dist}$ encodes both the set *S* of states and the probability function *P*.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] In this way, Markov decision processes could be generalized from monoids (categories with one object) to arbitrary categories.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] One can call the result $({\mathcal {C}},F:{\mathcal {C}}\to \mathbf {Dist} )$ a *context-dependent Markov decision process*, because moving from one object to another in ${\mathcal {C}}$ changes the set of available actions and the set of possible states.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] The terminology and notation for MDPs are not entirely settled.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/markov-decision-process] In addition, the notation for the transition probability varies.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] For example, in a grid maze, an agent learns to reach an exit worth 10 points.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] At a junction, Q-learning might assign a higher value to moving right than left if right gets to the exit faster, improving this choice by trying both directions over time.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] For any finite Markov decision process, *Q*-learning finds an optimal policy in the sense of maximizing the expected value of the total reward over any and all successive steps, starting from the current state.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] *Q*-learning can identify an optimal action-selection policy for any given finite Markov decision process, given infinite exploration time and a partly random policy.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] "Q" refers to the function that the algorithm computes: the expected reward—that is, the *quality*—of an action taken in a given state.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Reinforcement learning involves an agent, a set of *states* ${\mathcal {S}}$ , and a set ${\mathcal {A}}$ of *actions* per state.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] By performing an action $a\in {\mathcal {A}}$ , the agent transitions from state to state.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Executing an action in a specific state provides the agent with a *reward* (a numerical score).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] The goal of the agent is to maximize its total reward.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] It does this by adding the maximum reward attainable from future states to the reward for achieving its current state, effectively influencing the current action by the potential future reward.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] This potential reward is a weighted sum of expected values of the rewards of all future steps starting from the current state.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] As an example, consider the process of boarding a train, in which the reward is measured by the negative of the total time spent boarding (alternatively, the cost of boarding the train is equal to the boarding time).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] One strategy is to enter the train door as soon as they open, minimizing the initial wait time for yourself.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] If the train is crowded, however, then you will have a slow entry after the initial action of entering the door as people are fighting you to depart the train as you attempt to board.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] On the next day, by random chance (exploration), you decide to wait and let other people depart first.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] This initially results in a longer wait time.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] However, less time is spent fighting the departing passengers.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Through exploration, despite the initial (patient) action resulting in a larger cost (or negative reward) than in the forceful strategy, the overall cost is lower, thus revealing a more rewarding strategy.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] After $\Delta t$ steps into the future the agent will decide some next step.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] The weight for this step is calculated as $\gamma ^{\Delta t}$ , where $\gamma$ (the *discount factor*) is a number between 0 and 1 ( $0\leq \gamma \leq 1$ ).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Assuming $\gamma <1$ , it has the effect of valuing rewards received earlier higher than those received later (reflecting the value of a "good start"). $\gamma$ may also be interpreted as the probability to succeed (or survive) at every step $\Delta t$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Before learning begins, ⁠ Q ⁠ is initialized to a possibly arbitrary fixed value (chosen by the programmer).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Then, at each time t the agent selects an action $A_{t}$ , observes a reward $R_{t+1}$ , enters a new state $S_{t+1}$ (that may depend on both the previous state $S_{t}$ and the selected action), and Q is updated.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] where *$R_{t+1}$* is the reward received when moving from the state $S_{t}$ to the state $S_{t+1}$ , and $\alpha$ is the learning rate $(0<\alpha \leq 1)$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] An episode of the algorithm ends when state $S_{t+1}$ is a final or *terminal state*.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] However, *Q*-learning can also learn in non-episodic tasks (as a result of the property of convergent infinite series).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] If the discount factor is lower than 1, the action values are finite even if the problem can contain infinite loops or paths.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] For all final states $s_{f}$ , $Q(s_{f},a)$ is never updated, but is set to the reward value r observed for state $s_{f}$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] In most cases, $Q(s_{f},a)$ can be taken to equal zero.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] The learning rate or *step size* determines to what extent newly acquired information overrides old information.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] A factor of 0 makes the agent learn nothing (exclusively exploiting prior knowledge), while a factor of 1 makes the agent consider only the most recent information (ignoring prior knowledge to explore possibilities).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] In fully deterministic environments, a learning rate of $\alpha _{t}=1$ is optimal.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] When the problem is stochastic, the algorithm converges under some technical conditions on the learning rate that require it to decrease to zero.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] In practice, often a constant learning rate is used, such as $\alpha _{t}=0.1$ for all t .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] The discount factor ⁠ $\gamma$ ⁠ determines the importance of future rewards.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] A factor of 0 will make the agent "myopic" (or short-sighted) by only considering current rewards, i.e. $r_{t}$ (in the update rule above), while a factor approaching 1 will make it strive for a long-term high reward.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] If the discount factor meets or exceeds 1, the action values may diverge.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] For ⁠ $\gamma =1$ ⁠, without a terminal state, or if the agent never reaches one, all environment histories become infinitely long, and utilities with additive, undiscounted rewards generally become infinite.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Even with a discount factor only slightly lower than 1, *Q*-function learning leads to propagation of errors and instabilities when the value function is approximated with an artificial neural network.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] In that case, starting with a lower discount factor and increasing it towards its final value accelerates learning.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Since *Q*-learning is an iterative algorithm, it implicitly assumes an initial condition before the first update occurs.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] High initial values, also known as "optimistic initial conditions", can encourage exploration: no matter what action is selected, the update rule will cause it to have lower values than the other alternative, thus increasing their choice probability.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] The first reward r can be used to reset the initial conditions.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] According to this idea, the first time an action is taken the reward is used to set the value of Q .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] This allows immediate learning in case of fixed deterministic rewards.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] A model that incorporates *reset of initial conditions* (RIC) is expected to predict participants' behavior better than a model that assumes any *arbitrary initial condition* (AIC).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] RIC seems to be consistent with human behaviour in repeated binary choice experiments.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] One solution is to use an (adapted) artificial neural network as a function approximator.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Another possibility is to integrate Fuzzy Rule Interpolation (FRI) and use sparse fuzzy rule-bases instead of discrete Q-tables or ANNs, which has the advantage of being a human-readable knowledge representation form.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Function approximation may speed up learning in finite problems, due to the fact that the algorithm can generalize earlier experiences to previously unseen states.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Another technique to decrease the state/action space quantizes possible values.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Consider the example of learning to balance a stick on a finger.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] To describe a state at a certain point in time involves the position of the finger in space, its velocity, the angle of the stick and the angular velocity of the stick.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] This yields a four-element vector that describes one state, i.e. a snapshot of one state encoded into four values.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] The problem is that infinitely many possible states are present.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] To shrink the possible space of valid actions multiple values can be assigned to a bucket.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] The exact distance of the finger from its starting position (-Infinity to Infinity) is not known, but rather whether it is far away or not (Near, Far).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] The term "secondary reinforcement" is borrowed from animal learning theory, to model state values via backpropagation: the state value ⁠ $v(s')$ ⁠ of the consequence situation is backpropagated to the previously encountered situations.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] CAA computes state values vertically and actions horizontally (the "crossbar").
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Demonstration graphs showing delayed reinforcement learning contained states (desirable, undesirable, and neutral states), which were computed by the state evaluation function.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] This learning system was a forerunner of the Q-learning algorithm.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] In 2014, Google DeepMind patented an application of Q-learning to deep learning, entitled "deep reinforcement learning" or "deep Q-learning," that can play Atari 2600 games at expert human levels.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] The DeepMind system used a deep convolutional neural network, with layers of tiled convolutional filters to mimic the effects of receptive fields.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Reinforcement learning is unstable or divergent when a nonlinear function approximator such as a neural network is used to represent Q.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] This instability comes from the correlations present in the sequence of observations, the fact that small updates to Q may significantly change the policy of the agent and the data distribution, and the correlations between Q and the target values.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] The method can be used for stochastic search in various domains and applications.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] The technique used *experience replay,* a biologically inspired mechanism that uses a random sample of prior actions instead of the most recent action to proceed.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] This removes correlations in the observation sequence and smooths changes in the data distribution.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Iterative updates adjust Q towards target values that are only periodically updated, further reducing correlations with the target.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Because the future maximum approximated action value in Q-learning is evaluated using the same Q function as in current action selection policy, in noisy environments Q-learning can sometimes overestimate the action values, slowing the learning.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] A variant called Double Q-learning was proposed to correct this.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Double Q-learning is an off-policy reinforcement learning algorithm, where a different policy is used for value evaluation than what is used to select the next action.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] In practice, two separate value functions $Q^{A}$ and $Q^{B}$ are trained in a mutually symmetric fashion using separate experiences.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Now the estimated value of the discounted future is evaluated using a different policy, which solves the overestimation issue.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] This algorithm was later modified in 2015 and combined with deep learning, as in the DQN algorithm, resulting in Double DQN, which outperforms the original DQN algorithm.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Delayed Q-learning is an alternative implementation of the online *Q*-learning algorithm, with probably approximately correct (PAC) learning.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Greedy GQ is a variant of *Q*-learning to use in combination with (linear) function approximation.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] The advantage of Greedy GQ is that convergence is guaranteed even when function approximation is used to estimate the action values.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Distributional Q-learning is a variant of *Q*-learning which seeks to model the distribution of returns rather than the expected return of each action.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] It has been observed to facilitate estimate by deep neural networks and can enable alternative control methods, such as risk-sensitive control.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Q-learning has been proposed in the multi-agent setting (see Section 4.1.2 in ).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] One approach consists in pretending the environment is passive.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Littman proposes the minimax Q learning algorithm.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] The standard Q-learning algorithm (using a Q table) applies only to discrete action and state spaces.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] Discretization of these values leads to inefficient learning, largely due to the curse of dimensionality.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/q-learning] However, there are adaptations of Q-learning that attempt to solve this problem such as Wire-fitted Neural Network Q-Learning.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] In machine learning and optimal control, **reinforcement learning** (**RL**) is concerned with how an intelligent agent should take actions in a dynamic environment in order to maximize a reward signal.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Reinforcement learning is one of the three basic machine learning paradigms, alongside supervised learning and unsupervised learning.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] While supervised learning and unsupervised learning algorithms respectively attempt to discover patterns in labeled and unlabeled data, reinforcement learning involves training an agent through interactions with its environment.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] To learn to maximize rewards from these interactions, the agent makes decisions between trying new actions to learn more about the environment (exploration), or using current knowledge of the environment to take the best action (exploitation).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The search for the optimal balance between these two strategies is known as the exploration–exploitation dilemma.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The environment is typically stated in the form of a Markov decision process, as many reinforcement learning algorithms use dynamic programming techniques.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The main difference between classical dynamic programming methods and reinforcement learning algorithms is that the latter do not assume knowledge of an exact mathematical model of the Markov decision process, and they target large Markov decision processes where exact methods become infeasible.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Due to its generality, reinforcement learning is studied in many disciplines, such as game theory, control theory, operations research, information theory, simulation-based optimization, multi-agent systems, swarm intelligence, and statistics.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The purpose of reinforcement learning is for the agent to learn an optimal (or near-optimal) policy that maximizes the reward function or other user-provided reinforcement signal that accumulates from immediate rewards.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] This is similar to processes that appear to occur in animal psychology.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] For example, biological brains are hardwired to interpret signals such as pain and hunger as negative reinforcements, and interpret pleasure and food intake as positive reinforcements.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] In some circumstances, animals learn to adopt behaviors that optimize these rewards.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] This suggests that animals are capable of reinforcement learning.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] A basic reinforcement learning agent interacts with its environment in discrete time steps.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] At each time step t, the agent receives the current state $S_{t}$ and reward $R_{t}$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] It then chooses an action $A_{t}$ from the set of available actions, which is subsequently sent to the environment.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The environment moves to a new state $S_{t+1}$ and the reward $R_{t+1}$ associated with the *transition* $(S_{t},A_{t},S_{t+1})$ is determined.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] that maximizes the expected cumulative reward.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Formulating the problem as a Markov decision process assumes the agent directly observes the current environmental state; in this case, the problem is said to have *full observability*.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] If the agent only has access to a subset of states, or if the observed states are corrupted by noise, the agent is said to have *partial observability*, and formally the problem must be formulated as a partially observable Markov decision process.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] In both cases, the set of actions available to the agent can be restricted.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] For example, the state of an account balance could be restricted to be positive; if the current value of the state is 3 and the state transition attempts to reduce the value by 4, the transition will not be allowed.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] When the agent's performance is compared to that of an agent that acts optimally, the difference in performance yields the notion of regret.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] In order to act near optimally, the agent must reason about long-term consequences of its actions (i.e., maximize future rewards), although the immediate reward associated with this might be negative.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Thus, reinforcement learning is particularly well-suited to problems that include a long-term versus short-term reward trade-off.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] It has been applied successfully to various problems, including energy storage, robot control, photovoltaic generators, backgammon, checkers, Go (AlphaGo), and autonomous driving systems.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Two elements make reinforcement learning powerful: the use of samples to optimize performance, and the use of function approximation to deal with large environments.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The first two of these problems could be considered planning problems (since some form of model is available), while the last one could be considered to be a genuine learning problem.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] However, reinforcement learning converts both planning problems to machine learning problems.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The trade-off between exploration and exploitation has been most thoroughly studied through the multi-armed bandit problem and for finite state space Markov decision processes in Burnetas and Katehakis (1997).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Reinforcement learning requires clever exploration mechanisms; randomly selecting actions, without reference to an estimated probability distribution, shows poor performance.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The case of (small) finite Markov decision processes is relatively well understood.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] However, due to the lack of algorithms that scale well with the number of states (or scale to problems with infinite state spaces), simple exploration methods are the most practical.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] One such method is $\varepsilon$ -greedy, where $0<\varepsilon <1$ is a parameter controlling the amount of exploration vs. exploitation.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] With probability $1-\varepsilon$ , exploitation is chosen, and the agent chooses the action that it believes has the best long-term effect (ties between actions are broken uniformly at random).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Alternatively, with probability $\varepsilon$ , exploration is chosen, and the action is chosen uniformly at random. $\varepsilon$ is usually a fixed parameter but can be adjusted either according to a schedule (making the agent explore progressively less), or adaptively based on heuristics.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Even if the issue of exploration is disregarded and even if the state was observable (assumed hereafter), the problem remains to use past experience to find out which actions lead to higher cumulative rewards.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The policy map gives the probability of taking action a when in state s .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] There are also deterministic policies $\pi$ for which $\pi (s)$ denotes the action that should be played at state s .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The state-value function $V_{\pi }(s)$ is defined as, *expected discounted return* starting with state s , i.e. $S_{0}=s$ , and successively following policy $\pi$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Hence, roughly speaking, the value function estimates "how good" it is to be in a given state.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] where $R_{t+1}$ is the reward for transitioning from state $S_{t}$ to $S_{t+1}$ , $0\leq \gamma <1$ is the discount rate. $\gamma$ is less than 1, so rewards in the distant future are weighted less than rewards in the immediate future.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The algorithm must find a policy with maximum expected discounted return.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] From the theory of Markov decision processes it is known that, without loss of generality, the search can be restricted to the set of so-called *stationary* policies.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] A policy is *stationary* if the action-distribution returned by it depends only on the last state visited (from the observation agent's history).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The search can be further restricted to *deterministic* stationary policies.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] A *deterministic stationary* policy deterministically selects actions based on the current state.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Since any such policy can be identified with a mapping from the set of states to the set of actions, these policies can be identified with such mappings with no loss of generality.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] One problem with this is that the number of policies can be large, or even infinite.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Another is that the variance of the returns may be large, which requires many samples to accurately estimate the discounted return of each policy.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] These problems can be ameliorated if we assume some structure and allow samples generated from one policy to influence the estimates made for others.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The two main approaches for achieving this are value function estimation and direct policy search.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Value function approaches attempt to find a policy that maximizes the discounted return by maintaining a set of estimates of expected discounted returns $\operatorname {\mathbb {E} } [G]$ for some policy (usually either the "current" [on-policy] or the optimal [off-policy] one).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] These methods rely on the theory of Markov decision processes, where optimality is defined in a sense stronger than the one above: A policy is optimal if it achieves the best-expected discounted return from *any* initial state (i.e., initial distributions play no role in this definition).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Again, an optimal policy can always be found among stationary policies.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] where G stands for the discounted return associated with following $\pi$ from the initial state s .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] A policy that achieves these optimal state-values in each state is called *optimal*.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Clearly, a policy that is optimal in this sense is also optimal in the sense that it maximizes the expected discounted return, since $V^{*}(s)=\max _{\pi }\mathbb {E} [G\mid s,\pi ]$ , where s is a state randomly sampled from the distribution $\mu$ of initial states (so $\mu (s)=\Pr(S_{0}=s)$ ).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Although state-values suffice to define optimality, it is useful to define action-values.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] where G now stands for the random discounted return associated with first taking action a in state s and following $\pi$ , thereafter.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The theory of Markov decision processes states that if $\pi ^{*}$ is an optimal policy, we act optimally (take the optimal action) by choosing the action from $Q^{\pi ^{*}}(s,\cdot )$ with the highest action-value at each state, s .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The *action-value function* of such an optimal policy ( $Q^{\pi ^{*}}$ ) is called the *optimal action-value function* and is commonly denoted by $Q^{*}$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] In summary, the knowledge of the optimal action-value function alone suffices to know how to act optimally.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Assuming full knowledge of the Markov decision process, the two basic approaches to compute the optimal action-value function are value iteration and policy iteration.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Both algorithms compute a sequence of functions $Q_{k}$ ( $k=0,1,2,\ldots$ ) that converge to $Q^{*}$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Computing these functions involves computing expectations over the whole state-space, which is impractical for all but the smallest (finite) Markov decision processes.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] In reinforcement learning methods, expectations are approximated by averaging over samples and using function approximation techniques to cope with the need to represent value functions over large state-action spaces.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Monte Carlo methods are used to solve reinforcement learning problems by averaging sample returns.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Unlike methods that require full knowledge of the environment's dynamics, Monte Carlo methods rely solely on actual or simulated experience—sequences of states, actions, and rewards obtained from interaction with an environment.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] This makes them applicable in situations where the complete dynamics are unknown.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Learning from actual experience does not require prior knowledge of the environment and can still lead to optimal behavior.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] When using simulated experience, only a model capable of generating sample transitions is required, rather than a full specification of transition probabilities, which is necessary for dynamic programming methods.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Monte Carlo methods apply to episodic tasks, where experience is divided into episodes that eventually terminate.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Policy and value function updates occur only after the completion of an episode, making these methods incremental on an episode-by-episode basis, though not on a step-by-step (online) basis.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The term "Monte Carlo" generally refers to any method involving random sampling; however, in this context, it specifically refers to methods that compute averages from *complete* returns, rather than *partial* returns.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] These methods function similarly to the bandit algorithms, in which returns are averaged for each state-action pair.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The key difference is that actions taken in one state affect the returns of subsequent states within the same episode, making the problem non-stationary.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] To address this non-stationarity, Monte Carlo methods use the framework of general policy iteration (GPI).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] While dynamic programming computes value functions using full knowledge of the Markov decision process, Monte Carlo methods learn these functions through sample returns.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The value functions and policies interact similarly to dynamic programming to achieve optimality, first addressing the prediction problem and then extending to policy improvement and control, all based on sampled experience.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The first problem is corrected by allowing the procedure to change the policy (at some or all states) before the values settle.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] This too may be problematic as it might prevent convergence.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Most current algorithms do this, giving rise to the class of *generalized policy iteration* algorithms.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Many *actor-critic* methods belong to this category.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The second issue can be corrected by allowing trajectories to contribute to any state-action pair in them.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] This may also help to some extent with the third problem, although a better solution when returns have high variance is Sutton's temporal difference (TD) methods that are based on the recursive Bellman equation.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The computation in TD methods can be incremental (when after each transition the memory is changed and the transition is thrown away), or batch (when the transitions are batched and the estimates are computed once based on the batch).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Batch methods, such as the least-squares temporal difference method, may use the information in the samples better, while incremental methods are the only choice when batch methods are infeasible due to their high computational or memory complexity.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Some methods try to combine the two approaches.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Methods based on temporal differences also overcome the fourth issue.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Another problem specific to TD comes from their reliance on the recursive Bellman equation.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Most TD methods have a so-called $\lambda$ parameter $(0\leq \lambda \leq 1)$ that can continuously interpolate between Monte Carlo methods that do not rely on the Bellman equations and the basic TD methods that rely entirely on the Bellman equations.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] This can be effective in palliating this issue.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] In order to address the fifth issue, *function approximation methods* are used.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] *Linear function approximation* starts with a mapping $\phi$ that assigns a finite-dimensional vector to each state-action pair.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The algorithms then adjust the weights, instead of adjusting the values associated with the individual state-action pairs.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Methods based on ideas from nonparametric statistics (which can be seen to construct their own features) have been explored.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Value iteration can also be used as a starting point, giving rise to the Q-learning algorithm and its many variants.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Including Deep Q-learning methods when a neural network is used to represent Q, with various applications in stochastic search problems.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The problem with using action-values is that they may need highly precise estimates of the competing action values that can be hard to obtain when the returns are noisy, though this problem is mitigated to some extent by temporal difference methods.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Using the so-called compatible function approximation method compromises generality and efficiency.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] An alternative method is to search directly in (some subset of) the policy space, in which case the problem becomes a case of stochastic optimization.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The two approaches available are gradient-based and gradient-free methods.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Gradient-based methods (*policy gradient methods*) start with a mapping from a finite-dimensional (parameter) space to the space of policies: given the parameter vector $\theta$ , let $\pi _{\theta }$ denote the policy associated to $\theta$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Defining the performance function by $\rho (\theta )=\rho ^{\pi _{\theta }}$ under mild conditions this function will be differentiable as a function of the parameter vector $\theta$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] If the gradient of $\rho$ was known, one could use gradient ascent.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Since an analytic expression for the gradient is not available, only a noisy estimate is available.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Such an estimate can be constructed in many ways, giving rise to algorithms such as Williams's REINFORCE method (which is known as the likelihood ratio method in the simulation-based optimization literature).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] A large class of methods avoids relying on gradient information.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] These include simulated annealing, cross-entropy search or methods of evolutionary computation.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Many gradient-free methods can achieve (in theory and in the limit) a global optimum.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Policy search methods may converge slowly given noisy data.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] For example, this happens in episodic problems when the trajectories are long and the variance of the returns is large.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Value-function based methods that rely on temporal differences might help in this case.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] In recent years, *actor–critic methods* have been proposed and performed well on various problems.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Policy search methods have been used in the robotics context.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Many policy search methods may get stuck in local optima (as they are based on local search).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Finally, all of the above methods can be combined with algorithms that first learn a model of the Markov decision process, the probability of each next state given an action taken from an existing state.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] For instance, the Dyna algorithm learns a model from experience, and uses that to provide more modelled transitions for a value function, in addition to the real transitions.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Such methods can sometimes be extended to use of non-parametric models, such as when the transitions are simply stored and "replayed" to the learning algorithm.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Model-based methods can be more computationally intensive than model-free approaches, and their utility can be limited by the extent to which the Markov decision process can be learnt.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] There are other ways to use models than to update a value function.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] For instance, in model predictive control the model is used to update the behavior directly.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The costly exploration needed to learn an optimal policy can be reduced if some supervised data is available.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] This can be achieved for instance by learning a crude control policy and using this to initialize the Q table intelligently instead of with zeros.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Both the asymptotic and finite-sample behaviors of most algorithms are well understood.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Algorithms with provably (i.e. in a way that can be proved) good online performance (addressing the exploration issue) are known.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Efficient exploration of Markov decision processes is given in Burnetas and Katehakis (1997).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Finite-time performance bounds have also appeared for many algorithms, but these bounds are expected to be rather loose and thus more work is needed to better understand the relative advantages and limitations.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] For incremental algorithms, asymptotic convergence issues have been settled.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Temporal-difference-based algorithms converge under a wider set of conditions than was previously possible (for example, when used with arbitrary, smooth function approximation).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Associative reinforcement learning tasks combine facets of stochastic learning automata tasks and supervised learning pattern classification tasks.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] In associative reinforcement learning tasks, the learning system interacts in a closed loop with its environment.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] This approach extends reinforcement learning by using a deep neural network and without explicitly designing the state space.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The work on learning ATARI games by Google DeepMind increased attention to deep reinforcement learning or end-to-end reinforcement learning.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Adversarial deep reinforcement learning is an active area of research in reinforcement learning focusing on vulnerabilities of learned policies.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] In this research area some studies initially showed that reinforcement learning policies are susceptible to imperceptible adversarial manipulations.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] While some methods have been proposed to overcome these susceptibilities, in the most recent studies it has been shown that these proposed solutions are far from providing an accurate representation of current vulnerabilities of deep reinforcement learning policies.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] By introducing fuzzy inference in reinforcement learning, approximating the state-action value function with fuzzy rules in continuous space becomes possible.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The IF - THEN form of fuzzy rules make this approach suitable for expressing the results in a form close to natural language.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Extending FRL with Fuzzy Rule Interpolation allows the use of reduced size sparse fuzzy rule-bases to emphasize cardinal rules (most important state-action values).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] In inverse reinforcement learning (IRL), no reward function is given.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Instead, the reward function is inferred given an observed behavior from an expert.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The idea is to mimic observed behavior, which is often optimal or close to optimal.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] One popular IRL paradigm is named maximum entropy inverse reinforcement learning (MaxEnt IRL).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] MaxEnt IRL estimates the parameters of a linear model of the reward function by maximizing the entropy of the probability distribution of observed trajectories subject to constraints related to matching expected feature counts.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Recently it has been shown that MaxEnt IRL is a particular case of a more general framework named random utility inverse reinforcement learning (RU-IRL).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] RU-IRL is based on random utility theory and Markov decision processes.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The utility function is modeled as a random variable to account for the ignorance of the observer regarding the features the observed agent actually considers in its utility function.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Multi-objective reinforcement learning (MORL) is a form of reinforcement learning concerned with conflicting alternatives.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] It is distinct from multi-objective optimization in that it is concerned with agents acting in environments.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Safe reinforcement learning (SRL) can be defined as the process of learning policies that maximize the expectation of the return in problems in which it is important to ensure reasonable system performance and/or respect safety constraints during the learning and/or deployment processes.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] An alternative approach is risk-averse reinforcement learning, where instead of the *expected* return, a *risk-measure* of the return is optimized, such as the conditional value at risk (CVaR).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] In addition to mitigating risk, the CVaR objective increases robustness to model uncertainties.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] However, CVaR optimization in risk-averse RL requires special care, to prevent gradient bias and blindness to success.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Self-reinforcement learning (or self-learning), is a learning paradigm which does not use the concept of immediate reward $R_{a}(s,s')$ after transition from s to $s'$ with action a .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] It does not use an external reinforcement, it only uses the agent internal self-reinforcement.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The internal self-reinforcement is provided by mechanism of feelings and emotions.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] In the learning process emotions are backpropagated by a mechanism of secondary reinforcement.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The learning equation does not include the immediate reward, it only includes the state evaluation.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Compute state evaluation $v(s')$ of how good it is to be in the consequence situation $s'$ .
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Initial conditions of the memory are received as input from the genetic environment.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] It is a system with only one input (situation), and only one output (action, or behavior).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Self-reinforcement (self-learning) was introduced in 1982 along with a neural network capable of self-reinforcement learning, named Crossbar Adaptive Array (CAA).
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The CAA computes, in a crossbar fashion, both decisions about actions and emotions (feelings) about consequence states.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The system is driven by the interaction between cognition and emotion.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Efficient comparison of RL algorithms is essential for research, deployment and monitoring of RL systems.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] To compare different algorithms on a given environment, an agent can be trained for each algorithm.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Since the performance is sensitive to implementation details, all algorithms should be implemented as closely as possible to each other.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] After the training is finished, the agents can be run on a sample of test episodes, and their scores (returns) can be compared.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Since episodes are typically assumed to be i.i.d, standard statistical tools can be used for hypothesis testing, such as T-test and permutation test.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] This requires to accumulate all the rewards within an episode into a single number—the episodic return.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] However, this causes a loss of information, as different time-steps are averaged together, possibly with different levels of noise.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Whenever the noise level varies across the episode, the statistical power can be improved significantly, by weighting the rewards according to their estimated noise.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Despite significant advancements, reinforcement learning (RL) continues to face several challenges and limitations that hinder its widespread application in real-world scenarios.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] RL algorithms often require a large number of interactions with the environment to learn effective policies, leading to high computational costs and time-intensive to train the agent.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] For instance, OpenAI's Dota-playing bot utilized thousands of years of simulated gameplay to achieve human-level performance.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Techniques like experience replay and curriculum learning have been proposed to reduce sample inefficiency, but these techniques add more complexity and are not always sufficient for real-world applications.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Training RL models, particularly for deep neural network-based models, can be unstable and prone to divergence.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] A small change in the policy or environment can lead to extreme fluctuations in performance, making it difficult to achieve consistent results.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] This instability is further enhanced in the case of the continuous or high-dimensional action space, where the learning step becomes more complex and less predictable.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The RL agents trained in specific environments often struggle to generalize their learned policies to new, unseen scenarios.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] This is the major setback preventing the application of RL to dynamic real-world environments where adaptability is crucial.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] The challenge is to develop such algorithms that can transfer knowledge across tasks and environments without extensive retraining.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Designing appropriate reward functions is critical in RL because poorly designed reward functions can lead to unintended behaviors.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] In addition, RL systems trained on biased data may perpetuate existing biases and lead to discriminatory or unfair outcomes.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Both of these issues requires careful consideration of reward structures and data sources to ensure fairness and desired behaviors.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] In recent years Since the early 2020s, reinforcement learning has become a significant concept in natural language processing (NLP), where tasks are often sequential decision-making rather than static classification.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Reinforcement learning is where an agent take actions in an environment to maximize the accumulation of rewards.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] This framework is best fit for many NLP tasks, including dialogue generation, text summarization, and machine translation, where the quality of the output depends on optimizing long-term or human-centered goals rather than the prediction of single correct label.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Early application of RL in NLP emerged in dialogue systems, where conversation was determined as a series of actions optimized for fluency and coherence.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] These early attempts, including policy gradient and sequence-level training techniques, laid a foundation for the broader application of reinforcement learning to other areas of NLP.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] A major breakthrough happened with the introduction of reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF), a method in which human feedback ratings are used to train a reward model that guides the RL agent.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] Unlike traditional rule-based or supervised systems, RLHF allows models to align their behavior with human judgments on complex and subjective tasks.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] This technique was initially used in the development of InstructGPT, an effective language model trained to follow human instructions and later in ChatGPT which incorporates RLHF for improving output responses and ensuring safety.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] More recently, researchers have explored the use of offline RL in NLP to improve dialogue systems without the need of live human interaction.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] These methods optimize for user engagement, coherence, and diversity based on past conversation logs and pre-trained reward models.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] One example is DeepSeek-R1, which incorporates multi-stage training and cold-start data before RL.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] DeepSeek-R1 achieves performance comparable to OpenAI-o1-1217 on reasoning tasks.
[src:deep-reinforcement-learning/reinforcement-learning] This model was trained via large-scale RL without supervised fine-tuning (SFT) as a preliminary step.
